  "caption": "Tokyo nights done right!🇯🇵\nGolden Gai lives up to the hype :)\nMy POV: Plan time for more than one visit! \n\nBeen there? Share your experience in the comments! ⬇️\n\n(Golden Gai Tokyo Japan, Shinjuku izakaya, Japan travel tips, Japan 2026,Tokyo bar hopping, Japan nightlife guide)",
  "transcript": "If you go all the way to Tokyo and skip Golden Gai, we can't be friends. Welcome back to 30 Days in Japan. Golden Gai in Sinjuku is one of the coolest bar streets in all of Japan that was built on old train tracks where people used to pee. Now it homes around 200 tiny izakayas across 6 narrow alley lanes. These tiny izakayas fit 5-6% max. It's like you're drinking sake in someone's living room and hoping someone doesn't need to stand up. We got obsessed and went 3 nights in a row but still barely scratched the surface. One night we walked into this tiny bar where the owner was singing live jazz and I seriously got chills. Then we ended up at a goth bar with black walls and all these candles. The other night the owner was a magician. We also landed up at this place called Bar Taki. Jazz posters everywhere, vinyl playing and easily one of the best whiskey highballs you'll find in all of Japan. That's the thing about Golden Gai. Every single door opens into this completely different world. Some bars are members only and some are only open for locals. Not in a rude way. They want regulars who stand on night rather than people who just hop there for one drink. So if you see a foreigner's welcome sign and the bartender waves at you, you're all good. If not, move on, there are plenty. Most places will have a small cover charge but they give you bar snacks instead and these places are so tiny that you end up talking to everybody. We met a photographer from Osaka, this couple that was travelling from Berlin and some locals who've been coming there for 20 years. If you are into all of this, Golden Gai has to be near itinerary. Comment cocktail and I'll send you all of the bars that we went to.",
